      <exercise xml:id="Ez_10_4_-1"> 
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>f</m> be the function defined by <m>f(x,y) = 2x^2+3y^3</m>. 
          </p>

          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                Find the equation of the tangent plane to <m>f</m> at the point <m>(1,2)</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Use the linearization to approximate the values of <m>f</m> at the points <m>(1.1, 2.05)</m> and <m>(1.3,2.2)</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Compare the approximations form part (b) to the exact values of <m>f(1.1, 2.05)</m> and <m>f(1.3, 2.2)</m>. Which approximation is more accurate. Explain why this should be expected. 
              </p>
            </li>

          </ol>
        </statement>


        <answer>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <me>
                  z = 4(x-1) + 36(y-2) + 26
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>  
            <li>
              <p>
                <me>
                  f(1.1,2.05) \approx L(1.1, 2.5) = 28.2
                </me> 
                and
                <me>
                  f(1.3, 2.2) \approx L(1.3, 2.2) = 34.4
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                We have
                <me>
                  f(1.1, 2.05) = 2(1.1)^2 + 3(2.05)^3 = 28.265375
                </me>. Since <m>L(1.1, 2.05) = 28.2</m>, our approximation differs by 0.065375.
                For our second value we have 
                <me>
                  f(1.3,2.2) \2(1.3)^2 + 3(2.2)^3 = 35.324
                </me>.
                Our approximation was <m>L(1.3, 2.2) = 34.4</m>, so this time the difference between the approximate value and the actual value is 0.924. 
              </p>
              <p>
                Notice that our approximation for <m>f(1.1, 2.05)</m> was closer to the actual value. This is to be expected because we found the linearization using the tangent plane to <m>f</m> at <m>(1, 2)</m>, and the point <m>(1.1, 2.05)</m> is closer to <m>(1, 2)</m> than <m>(1.3, 2,2)</m> is.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>  
        </answer>

        <solution>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                Since <m>\frac{\partial f}{\partial x} = 4x</m> and <m>\frac{\partial f}{\partial y} = 9y^2</m> we have
                <m>f_x(1,2) = 4</m> and <m>f_y(1,2) = 36</m>. Note that <m>f(1, 2) = 2 + 24 = 26.</m>
                So the equation of the plane tangent to <m>f</m> at <m>(1,2)</m> is
                <me>
                  z = f_x(1,2)(x-1) + f_y(1,2)(y-2) + f(1,2)
                </me>
                or
                <me>
                  z = 4(x-1) + 36(y-2) + 26
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>  
            <li>
              <p>
                The linearization, as given by the tangent plane, is
                <me>
                  L(x ,y) = 4(x-1) + 36(y-2) + 26
                </me>.
                Thus 
                <md>
                  <mrow> f(1.1,2.05)  \amp  \approx L(1.1, 2.5) = 4(1.1-1) + 36(2.05-2) + 26</mrow>
                  <mrow> \amp = 4(0.1) + 36(0.05) + 26 = 28.2 </mrow>
                </md>
                and
                <md>
                  <mrow> f(1.3, 2.2) \amp \approx L(1.3, 2.2) = 4(1.3-1) + 36(2.2-2) + 26</mrow>
                  <mrow> \amp = 4(0.3) + 36(0.2) + 26 = 34.4 </mrow> 
                </md>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                We have
                <me>
                  f(1.1, 2.05) = 2(1.1)^2 + 3(2.05)^3 = 28.265375
                </me>. 
                Since <m>L(1.1, 2.05) = 28.2</m>, our approximation differs by 0.065375.
                For our second value we have 
                <me>
                  f(1.3,2.2) = 2(1.3)^2 + 3(2.2)^3 = 35.324
                </me>.
                Our approximation was <m>L(1.3, 2.2) = 34.4</m>, so this time the difference between the approximate value and the actual value is 0.924. 
              </p>
              <p>
                Notice that our approximation for <m>f(1.1, 2.05)</m> was closer to the actual value. This is to be expected because we found the linearization using the tangent plane to <m>f</m> at <m>(1, 2)</m>, and the point <m>(1.1, 2.05)</m> is closer to <m>(1, 2)</m> than <m>(1.3, 2,2)</m> is.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>  
        </solution>
        
      </exercise>


      <exercise xml:id="Ez_10_4_0"> 
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>f</m> be the function defined by <m>f(x,y) = x^{1/3}y^{1/3}</m>, whose graph is shown in <xref ref="F_10_4_Not_diff">Figure</xref>.
          </p>

          <figure xml:id="F_10_4_Not_diff">
            <caption>The surface for <m>f(x,y) = x^{1/3}y^{1/3}</m>.</caption>
            <image width="50%" source="images/fig_10_4_not_diff"/>
          </figure>

          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                Determine
                <me>
                  \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(0+h,0)-f(0,0)}{h}.
                </me>
                What does this limit tell us about <m>f_x(0,0)</m>?
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Note that <m>f(x,y)=f(y,x)</m>, and this symmetry implies that <m>f_x(0,0) = f_y(0,0)</m>. So both partial derivatives of <m>f</m> exist at <m>(0,0)</m>. A picture of the surface defined by <m>f</m> near <m>(0,0)</m> is shown in <xref ref="F_10_4_Not_diff">Figure</xref>. Based on this picture, do you think <m>f</m> is locally linear at <m>(0,0)</m>? Why?
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Show that the curve where <m>x=y</m> on the surface defined by <m>f</m> is not differentiable at 0. What does this tell us about the local linearity of <m>f</m> at <m>(0,0)</m>?
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Is the function <m>f</m> defined by <m>f(x,y) = \frac{x^2}{y^2+1}</m> locally linear at <m>(0,0)</m>? Why or why not?
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </statement>

        <answer>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <me>
                  f_x(0,0) = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(0+h,0)-f(0,0)}{h} = 0
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The graph of <m>f</m> seems to indicate some kind of sharp fold in the surface around the point <m>(0,0)</m>,
                so it appears that <m>f</m> is not locally linear at <m>(0,0)</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                When <m>x=y</m>, <m>f</m> has the form <m>f(x,x) = x^{2/3}</m>.
                Now
                <me>
                  \frac{d f(x,x)}{dx} \biggm|_{x=0} = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{(0+h)^{2/3} - 0}{h} = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{h^{2/3}}{h} = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{1}{h^{1/3}}
                </me>
                is undefined.
                Since <m>f</m> does not have a derivative at <m>(0,0)</m> along the path <m>y=x</m>,
                it follows that <m>f</m> defined by
                <m>f(x,y) = x^{1/3}y^{1/3}</m> is not locally linear at <m>(0,0)</m>.
                Note that neither <m>f_x</m> nor <m>f_y</m> is continuous at <m>(0,0)</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                For <m>f(x,y) = \frac{x^2}{y^2+1}</m> we have
                <me>
                  f_x(x,y) = \frac{2x(y^2+1)}{(y^2+1)^2} \ \text{ and }  \ f_y(x,y) = \frac{-2x^2y}{(y^2+1)^2}
                </me>,
                both of which are continuous around <m>(0,0)</m>.
                So <m>f</m> is locally linear at <m>(0,0)</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </answer>

        <solution>
