      <exercise xml:id="Ez_10_4_5">
        <statement>
          <p>
             
              Suppose that a function <m>f = f(x,y)</m> is differentiable at a point <m>(x_0,y_0)</m>. Let <m>L = L(x,y) = f(x_0,y_0) + m(x-x_0) + n(y-y_0)</m> as in the conditions of <xref ref="Def_10_4_differentiability">Definition</xref>. Show that <m>m = f_x(x_0,y_0)</m> and <m>n = f_y(x_0,y_0)</m>. (Hint: Calculate the limits of the relative errors when <m>h = 0</m> and <m>k = 0</m>.)

          </p>
        </statement>

        <answer>
          <p>
            Assume that <m>f=f(x,y)</m> is differentiable at a point <m>(x_0, y_0)</m>. Then by definition there exists a linear function 
            <me>
              L(x, y) = f(x_0, y_0) + m(x - x_0) + n(y-y_0)
            </me>
            such that the relative error 
            <me>
              \frac{E(x_0 + h, y_0 + k)}{\sqrt{h^2 + k^2}}
            </me>
            goes to <m>0</m> as <m>(h, k)</m> goes to <m>(0,0)</m>, where <m>E(x, y) = f(x, y) - L(x, y), h = x - x_0, k = y-y_0</m>. Since we know that  this limit exists and is equal to <m>0</m> we know that the limit must be <m>0</m> along any path to <m>(0, 0)</m>.
          </p>

          <p>
            Consider the relative error. Along the path <m>h = 0</m> we have  
            <md>
              <mrow> \frac{E(x_0 + h, y_0 + k)}{\sqrt{h^2 + k^2}} \amp = \frac{E(x_0, y_0 + k)}{\sqrt{k^2}} </mrow>
              <mrow> \amp = \frac{f(x_0, y_0 + k) - L(x_0, y_0 + k)}{\sqrt{k^2}} </mrow>
              <mrow> \amp = \frac{f(x_0, y_0 + k) - \left ( f(x_0, y_0) + m(x_0 - x_0) + n(y_0 + k - y_0) \right )}{\sqrt{k^2}} </mrow>
              <mrow> \amp = \frac{\left ( f(x_0, y_0 + k) - f(x_0, y_0) \right ) - n(k)}{\vert k \vert }  </mrow>
            </md>.  
            Recall that 
            <me>
              f_y(x_0, y_0) = \lim_{k \to 0} \frac{ f(x_0, y_0 + k) - f(x_0, y_0)}{k}
            </me>.
            Since the limit of the relative error is <m>0</m> we must have  
            <md>
              <mrow> 0 \amp = \lim_{k \to 0} \frac{E(x_0 + h, y_0 + k)}{\sqrt{h^2 + k^2}} </mrow>
              <mrow> \amp = \lim_{k \to 0} \frac{\left ( f(x_0, y_0 + k) - f(x_0, y_0) \right ) - n(k)}{\vert k \vert } </mrow>
            </md>.
            From here we can show that 
            <md>
              <mrow> 0 \amp = \lim_{k \to 0} \frac{\left ( f(x_0, y_0 + k) - f(x_0, y_0) \right ) - n(k)}{k} </mrow>
              <mrow> \amp = \lim_{k \to 0} \left ( \frac{f(x_0, y_0 + k) - f(x_0, y_0) }{k} - n \right )</mrow>
            </md>
            which implies  
            <me>
              n = \lim_{k \to 0} \frac{f(x_0, y_0 + k) - f(x_0, y_0) }{k} = f_y(x_0, y_0) 
            </me>.
          </p>

          <p>
            Similiarly, by taking the limit along the path <m>k=0</m> we can show that 
            <me>
              m = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(x_0 + h, y_0) - f(x_0, y_0) }{k} = f_x(x_0, y_0) 
            </me>.
          </p>
        </answer>


